
Project Glass is a research and development program by Google to develop an augmented reality head-mounted display (HMD). The product (Google Glass Explorer Edition) will be available to United States Google I/O developers for $1500, shipping early in 2013.  CNET - Google Glass Explorer Edition
The intended purpose of Project Glass products would be the hands free displaying of information currently available to most smartphone users, 
Project Glass is part of the Google X Lab at the company,

== Prototypes ==

Though head-worn displays for augmented reality are not a new idea, the project has drawn media attention
The product began testing in April 2012. 
The New York Times reported that the glasses would be available to the public for "around the cost of current smartphones" by the end of 2012,
Google has patented the design of Project Glass.
On May 23, Sergey Brin demoed the glasses on The Gavin Newsom Show and let California Lieutenant Governor Gavin Newsom wear the glasses .
On June 27th, Sergey Brin demoed the glasses at Google I/O using skydivers, abseilers, and Mountain Bikers. http://techcrunch.com/2012/06/27/sergey-brin-demos-google-glass-at-io/

== Reception ==

Despite the generally positive reception for the prototype, there have been numerous parodies and criticisms aimed at the general notion of augmented reality glasses, ranging from the potential for Google to insert advertising (its main source of revenue) to more dystopian outcomes. Tom Merritt of TWiT famously confused this with SmartGlass.

